result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Attorney Puck Tsai in court.  Sue Mueller appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty Tsai advises DE was here but left.  Requests matter be set off the 1:00 p.m. calendar.  Matter reset.  Status hearing scheduled for March 7, 2017 at 01:00 pm.

Defendant Isaac DT Graham in court with attorney Puck Tsai.  Defendant Isaac DT Graham in custody.  Michael Albrecht appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court states case and parties state appearances.  Atty Tsai notes they are motioning to have the file transferred back to juvenile court.  Parties are not in agreement.  Court requests some clarification re: the motion.  Atty Tsai states some highlights of his motion that he already filed in writing.  State notes they object to an evidentiary hearing on the motion as it's insufficient but does think they will need one at the right time/makes argument.  Atty Tsai responds.  Court finds (5) and (6) were not followed by the Court and now wondering what to do.  Court doesn't believe an evidentiary hearing is necessary.  Court is concerned about the timing of the filing of these motions.  Court will relinquish jurisdiction of this matter back to juvenile court.  Atty Tsai states he will likely file a motion in the next few days asking the juvenile court to reconsider their waiver into adult court.  State will object to that.  Matter is adjourned.
